# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: procedural-generation-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] **CA**) is a discrete model of computation studied in automata theory.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata are also called **cellular spaces**, **tessellation automata**, **homogeneous structures**, **cellular structures**, **tessellation structures**, and **iterative arrays**.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have found application in various areas, including physics, theoretical biology, and microstructure modeling.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A cellular automaton consists of a regular grid of *cells*, each in one of a finite number of *states*, such as *on* and *off* (in contrast to a coupled map lattice).
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The grid can be in any finite number of dimensions.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For each cell, a set of cells called its *neighborhood* is defined relative to the specified cell.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] An initial state (time *t* = 0) is selected by assigning a state for each cell.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A new *generation* is created (advancing *t* by 1), according to some fixed *rule* (generally, a mathematical function) that determines the new state of each cell in terms of the current state of the cell and the states of the cells in its neighborhood.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Typically, the rule for updating the state of cells is the same for each cell and does not change over time, and is applied to the whole grid simultaneously, though exceptions are known, such as the stochastic cellular automaton and asynchronous cellular automaton.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The concept was originally conceived in the 1940s by Stanislaw Ulam and John von Neumann while they were contemporaries at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] While studied by some throughout the 1950s and 1960s, it was not until the 1970s and Conway's Game of Life, a two-dimensional cellular automaton, that interest in the subject expanded beyond academia.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the 1980s, Stephen Wolfram engaged in a systematic study of one-dimensional cellular automata, or what he calls elementary cellular automata; his research assistant Matthew Cook showed that one of these rules is Turing-complete.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The primary classifications of cellular automata, as outlined by Wolfram, are numbered one to four.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This last class is thought to be computationally universal, or capable of simulating a Turing machine.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Special types of cellular automata are *reversible*, where only a single configuration leads directly to a subsequent one, and *totalistic*, in which the future value of individual cells only depends on the total value of a group of neighboring cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata can simulate a variety of real-world systems, including biological and chemical ones.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The range-2 "cross neighborhood" includes the pink cells as well.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One way to simulate a two-dimensional cellular automaton is with an infinite sheet of graph paper along with a set of rules for the cells to follow.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Each square is called a "cell" and each cell has two possible states, black or white.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The *neighborhood* of a cell is the nearby, usually adjacent, cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The two most common types of neighborhoods are the *von Neumann neighborhood* and the *Moore neighborhood*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The former, named after the founding cellular automaton theorist, consists of the four orthogonally adjacent cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The latter includes the von Neumann neighborhood as well as the four diagonally adjacent cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For such a cell and its Moore neighborhood, there are 512 (= 29) possible patterns.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For each of the 512 possible patterns, the rule table would state whether the center cell will be black or white on the next time interval.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Conway's Game of Life is a popular version of this model.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Another common neighborhood type is the *extended von Neumann neighborhood*, which includes the two closest cells in each orthogonal direction, for a total of eight.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The general equation for the total number of automata possible is *k**k**s*, where *k* is the number of possible states for a cell, and *s* is the number of neighboring cells (including the cell to be calculated itself) used to determine the cell's next state.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Thus, in the two-dimensional system with a Moore neighborhood, the total number of automata possible would be 229, or 1.34×10154.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] It is usually assumed that every cell in the universe starts in the same state, except for a finite number of cells in other states; the assignment of state values is called a *configuration*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] More generally, it is sometimes assumed that the universe starts out covered with a periodic pattern, and only a finite number of cells violate that pattern.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The latter assumption is common in one-dimensional cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata are often simulated on a finite grid rather than an infinite one.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In two dimensions, the universe would be a rectangle instead of an infinite plane.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The obvious problem with finite grids is how to handle the cells on the edges.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] How they are handled will affect the values of all the cells in the grid.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One possible method is to allow the values in those cells to remain constant.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Another method is to define neighborhoods differently for these cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One could say that they have fewer neighbors, but then one would also have to define new rules for the cells located on the edges.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] These cells are usually handled with periodic boundary conditions resulting in a *toroidal* arrangement: when one goes off the top, one comes in at the corresponding position on the bottom, and when one goes off the left, one comes in on the right.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Universes of other dimensions are handled similarly.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This solves boundary problems with neighborhoods, but another advantage is that it is easily programmable using modular arithmetic functions.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For example, in a 1-dimensional cellular automaton like the examples below, the neighborhood of a cell *xit* is {*x**i*−1*t*−1, *x**i**t*−1, *x**i*+1*t*−1}, where *t* is the time step (vertical), and *i* is the index (horizontal) in one generation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Stanisław Ulam, while working at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in the 1940s, studied the growth of crystals, using a simple lattice network as his model.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] At the same time, John von Neumann — Ulam's colleague at Los Alamos — was working on the problem of self-replicating systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Von Neumann's initial design was founded upon the notion of one robot building another robot.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This design is known as the kinematic model.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] As he developed this design, von Neumann came to realize the great difficulty of building a self-replicating robot, and of the great cost in providing the robot with a "sea of parts" from which to build its replicant.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Neumann wrote a paper entitled "The general and logical theory of automata" for the Hixon Symposium in 1948.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Ulam was the one who suggested using a *discrete* system for creating a reductionist model of self-replication.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Nils Aall Barricelli performed many of the earliest explorations of these models of artificial life.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Ulam and von Neumann created a method for calculating liquid motion in the late 1950s.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The driving concept of the method was to consider a liquid as a group of discrete units and calculate the motion of each based on its neighbors' behaviors.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Thus was born the first system of cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Like Ulam's lattice network, von Neumann's cellular automata are two-dimensional, with his self-replicator implemented algorithmically.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The result was a universal copier and constructor working within a cellular automaton with a small neighborhood (only those cells that touch are neighbors; for von Neumann's cellular automata, only orthogonal cells), and with 29 states per cell.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Von Neumann gave an existence proof that a particular pattern would make endless copies of itself within the given cellular universe by designing a 200,000 cell configuration that could do so.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This design is known as the tessellation model, and is called a von Neumann universal constructor.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Also in the 1940s, Norbert Wiener and Arturo Rosenblueth developed a model of excitable media with some of the characteristics of a cellular automaton.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Their specific motivation was the mathematical description of impulse conduction in cardiac systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] However their model is not a cellular automaton because the medium in which signals propagate is continuous, and wave fronts are curves.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A true cellular automaton model of excitable media was developed and studied by J.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Hastings in 1978; see Greenberg-Hastings cellular automaton.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The original work of Wiener and Rosenblueth contains many insights and continues to be cited in modern research publications on cardiac arrhythmia and excitable systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the 1960s, cellular automata were studied as a particular type of dynamical system and the connection with the mathematical field of symbolic dynamics was established for the first time.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Hedlund compiled many results following this point of view in what is still considered as a seminal paper for the mathematical study of cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The most fundamental result is the characterization in the Curtis–Hedlund–Lyndon theorem of the set of global rules of cellular automata as the set of continuous endomorphisms of shift spaces.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Also in 1969 computer scientist Alvy Ray Smith completed a Stanford PhD dissertation on Cellular Automata Theory, the first mathematical treatment of CA as a general class of computers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Many papers came from this dissertation: He showed the equivalence of neighborhoods of various shapes, how to reduce a Moore to a von Neumann neighborhood or how to reduce any neighborhood to a von Neumann neighborhood.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] He proved that two-dimensional CA are computation universal, introduced 1-dimensional CA, and showed that they too are computation universal, even with simple neighborhoods.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] He showed how to subsume the complex von Neumann proof of construction universality (and hence self-reproducing machines) into a consequence of computation universality in a 1-dimensional CA.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Intended as the introduction to the German edition of von Neumann's book on CA, he wrote a survey of the field with dozens of references to papers, by many authors in many countries over a decade or so of work, often overlooked by modern CA researchers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the 1970s a two-state, two-dimensional cellular automaton named Game of Life became widely known, particularly among the early computing community.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Any live cell with two or three live neighbours lives on to the next generation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies, as if by overpopulation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell, as if by reproduction.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Despite its simplicity, the system achieves an impressive diversity of behavior, fluctuating between apparent randomness and order.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One of the most apparent features of the Game of Life is the frequent occurrence of *gliders*, arrangements of cells that essentially move themselves across the grid.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] It is possible to arrange the automaton so that the gliders interact to perform computations, and after much effort it has been shown that the Game of Life can emulate a universal Turing machine.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] It was viewed as a largely recreational topic, and little follow-up work was done outside of investigating the particularities of the Game of Life and a few related rules in the early 1970s.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Stephen Wolfram independently began working on cellular automata in mid-1981 after considering how complex patterns seemed formed in nature in violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] His investigations were initially spurred by a desire to model systems such as the neural networks found in brains.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] He published his first paper in *Reviews of Modern Physics* investigating *elementary cellular automata* (Rule 30 in particular) in June 1983.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The unexpected complexity of the behavior of these simple rules led Wolfram to suspect that complexity in nature may be due to similar mechanisms.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] His investigations, however, led him to realize that cellular automata were poor at modelling neural networks.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Additionally, during this period Wolfram formulated the concepts of intrinsic randomness and computational irreducibility, and suggested that Rule 110 may be universal—a fact proved later by Wolfram's research assistant Matthew Cook in the 1990s.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Wolfram, in *A New Kind of Science* and several papers dating from the mid-1980s, defined four classes into which cellular automata and several other simple computational models can be divided depending on their behavior.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] While earlier studies in cellular automata tended to try to identify types of patterns for specific rules, Wolfram's classification was the first attempt to classify the rules themselves.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] These definitions are qualitative in nature and there is some room for interpretation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] According to Wolfram, "...with almost any general classification scheme there are inevitably cases which get assigned to one class by one definition and another class by another definition.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] There have been several attempts to classify cellular automata in formally rigorous classes, inspired by Wolfram's classification.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For instance, Culik and Yu proposed three well-defined classes (and a fourth one for the automata not matching any of these), which are sometimes called Culik–Yu classes; membership in these proved undecidable.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Wolfram's class 2 can be partitioned into two subgroups of stable (fixed-point) and oscillating (periodic) rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A cellular automaton is *reversible* if, for every current configuration of the cellular automaton, there is exactly one past configuration (preimage).
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] If one thinks of a cellular automaton as a function mapping configurations to configurations, reversibility implies that this function is bijective.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] If a cellular automaton is reversible, its time-reversed behavior can also be described as a cellular automaton; this fact is a consequence of the Curtis–Hedlund–Lyndon theorem, a topological characterization of cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For cellular automata in which not every configuration has a preimage, the configurations without preimages are called *Garden of Eden* patterns.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For one-dimensional cellular automata there are known algorithms for deciding whether a rule is reversible or irreversible.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] However, for cellular automata of two or more dimensions reversibility is undecidable; that is, there is no algorithm that takes as input an automaton rule and is guaranteed to determine correctly whether the automaton is reversible.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The proof by Jarkko Kari is related to the tiling problem by Wang tiles.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] When a 2D automata is not reversible, often the proof can be trivial as distinct patterns that map to the same state can be quite common.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Reversible cellular automata are often used to simulate such physical phenomena as gas and fluid dynamics, since they obey the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Such cellular automata have rules specially constructed to be reversible.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Such systems have been studied by Tommaso Toffoli, Norman Margolus and others.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Several techniques can be used to explicitly construct reversible cellular automata with known inverses.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Two common ones are the second-order cellular automaton and the block cellular automaton, both of which involve modifying the definition of a cellular automaton in some way.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Although such automata do not strictly satisfy the definition given above, it can be shown that they can be emulated by conventional cellular automata with sufficiently large neighborhoods and numbers of states, and can therefore be considered a subset of conventional cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Conversely, it has been shown that every reversible cellular automaton can be emulated by a block cellular automaton.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A special class of cellular automata are *totalistic* cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The state of each cell in a totalistic cellular automaton is represented by a number (usually an integer value drawn from a finite set), and the value of a cell at time *t* depends only on the *sum* of the values of the cells in its neighborhood (possibly including the cell itself) at time *t* − 1.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] If the state of the cell at time *t* depends on both its own state and the total of its neighbors at time *t* − 1 then the cellular automaton is properly called *outer totalistic*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Conway's Game of Life is outer totalistic (but not totalistic), with cell values 0 and 1.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Outer totalistic cellular automata with the same Moore neighborhood structure as Life are sometimes called life-like cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] More generally, an *isotropic* ruleset is one that is not necessarily outer totalistic, but still has all the reflection symmetries.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the case of a cellular automata on a square grid, the group of symmetries is D8.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] There are many possible generalizations of the cellular automaton concept.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One way is by using something other than a rectangular (cubic, *etc.*) grid.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For example, if a plane is tiled with regular hexagons, those hexagons could be used as cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In many cases the resulting cellular automata are equivalent to those with rectangular grids with specially designed neighborhoods and rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Another variation would be to make the grid itself irregular, such as with Penrose tiles.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Also, rules can be probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Such cellular automata are called probabilistic cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A probabilistic rule gives, for each pattern at time *t*, the probabilities that the central cell will transition to each possible state at time *t* + 1.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The neighborhood or rules could change over time or space.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For example, initially the new state of a cell could be determined by the horizontally adjacent cells, but for the next generation the vertical cells would be used.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In cellular automata, the new state of a cell is not affected by the new state of other cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This could be changed so that, for instance, a 2 by 2 block of cells can be determined by itself and the cells adjacent to itself.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] These are like totalistic cellular automata, but instead of the rule and states being discrete (*e.g.* a table, using states {0,1,2}), continuous functions are used, and the states become continuous (usually values in [0,1]).
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The state of a location is a finite number of real numbers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Certain cellular automata can yield diffusion in liquid patterns in this way.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Continuous spatial automata have a continuum of locations.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Time is also continuous, and the state evolves according to differential equations.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One important example is reaction–diffusion textures, differential equations proposed by Alan Turing to explain how chemical reactions could create the stripes on zebras and spots on leopards.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] When these are approximated by cellular automata, they often yield similar patterns.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] MacLennan considers continuous spatial automata as a model of computation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] There are known examples of continuous spatial automata, which exhibit propagating phenomena analogous to gliders in the Game of Life.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The simplest nontrivial cellular automaton would be one-dimensional, with two possible states per cell, and a cell's neighbors defined as the adjacent cells on either side of it.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A cell and its two neighbors form a neighborhood of 3 cells, so there are 23 = 8 possible patterns for a neighborhood.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A rule consists of deciding, for each pattern, whether the cell will be a 1 or a 0 in the next generation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] These 256 cellular automata are generally referred to by their Wolfram code, a standard naming convention invented by Wolfram that gives each rule a number from 0 to 255.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A number of papers have analyzed and compared the distinct cases among the 256 cellular automata (many are trivially isomorphic).
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The rule 30, rule 90, rule 110, and rule 184 cellular automata are particularly interesting.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The images below show the history of rules 30 and 110 when the starting configuration consists of a 1 (at the top of each image) surrounded by 0s.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Each row of pixels represents a generation in the history of the automaton, with *t*=0 being the top row.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Each pixel is colored white for 0 and black for 1.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Rule 30 exhibits *class 3* behavior, meaning even simple input patterns such as that shown lead to chaotic, seemingly random histories.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Rule 110, like the Game of Life, exhibits what Wolfram calls *class 4* behavior, which is neither completely random nor completely repetitive.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Localized structures appear and interact in various complicated-looking ways.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the course of the development of *A New Kind of Science*, as a research assistant to Wolfram in 1994, Matthew Cook proved that some of these structures were rich enough to support universality.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This result is interesting because rule 110 is an extremely simple one-dimensional system, and difficult to engineer to perform specific behavior.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This result therefore provides significant support for Wolfram's view that class 4 systems are inherently likely to be universal.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cook presented his proof at a Santa Fe Institute conference on Cellular Automata in 1998, but Wolfram blocked the proof from being included in the conference proceedings, as Wolfram did not want the proof announced before the publication of *A New Kind of Science*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In 2004, Cook's proof was finally published in Wolfram's journal *Complex Systems* (Vol.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] 1), over ten years after Cook came up with it.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Rule 110 has been the basis for some of the smallest universal Turing machines.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] An elementary cellular automaton rule is specified by 8 bits, and all elementary cellular automaton rules can be considered to sit on the vertices of the 8-dimensional unit hypercube.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This unit hypercube is the cellular automaton rule space.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For next-nearest-neighbor cellular automata, a rule is specified by 25 = 32 bits, and the cellular automaton rule space is a 32-dimensional unit hypercube.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A distance between two rules can be defined by the number of steps required to move from one vertex, which represents the first rule, and another vertex, representing another rule, along the edge of the hypercube.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This rule-to-rule distance is also called the Hamming distance.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automaton rule space allows us to ask the question concerning whether rules with similar dynamical behavior are "close" to each other.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Graphically drawing a high dimensional hypercube on the 2-dimensional plane remains a difficult task, and one crude locator of a rule in the hypercube is the number of bit-1 in the 8-bit string for elementary rules (or 32-bit string for the next-nearest-neighbor rules).
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Drawing the rules in different Wolfram classes in these slices of the rule space show that class 1 rules tend to have lower number of bit-1s, thus located in one region of the space, whereas class 3 rules tend to have higher proportion (50%) of bit-1s.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For larger cellular automaton rule space, it is shown that class 4 rules are located between the class 1 and class 3 rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This observation is the foundation for the phrase edge of chaos, and is reminiscent of the phase transition in thermodynamics.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Several biological processes or phenomena can be simulated using cellular automata, which is regarded as a specific type of agent-based model in such application contexts.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In these biological simulations, it is common for the cells of the cellular automaton to be identified with biological cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Additionally, biological phenomena which require explicit modeling of the agents' velocities (for example, those involved in collective cell migration) may be modeled by cellular automata with a more complex state space and rules, such as biological lattice-gas cellular automata.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The Belousov–Zhabotinsky reaction is a spatio-temporal chemical oscillator that can be simulated by means of a cellular automaton.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Belousov) discovered that when a thin, homogenous layer of a mixture of malonic acid, acidified bromate, and a ceric salt were mixed together and left undisturbed, fascinating geometric patterns such as concentric circles and spirals propagate across the medium.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the "Computer Recreations" section of the August 1988 issue of *Scientific American*, A.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Dewdney discussed a cellular automaton developed by Martin Gerhardt and Heike Schuster of the University of Bielefeld (Germany).
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This automaton produces wave patterns that resemble those in the Belousov-Zhabotinsky reaction.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Probabilistic cellular automata are used in statistical and condensed matter physics to study phenomena like fluid dynamics and phase transitions.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The Ising model is a prototypical example, in which each cell can be in either of two states called "up" and "down", making an idealized representation of a magnet.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] By adjusting the parameters of the model, the proportion of cells being in the same state can be varied, in ways that help explicate how ferromagnets become demagnetized when heated.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Moreover, results from studying the demagnetization phase transition can be transferred to other phase transitions, like the evaporation of a liquid into a gas; this convenient cross-applicability is known as universality.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The phase transition in the two-dimensional Ising model and other systems in its universality class has been of particular interest, as it requires conformal field theory to understand in depth.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Other cellular automata that have been of significance in physics include lattice gas automata, which simulate fluid flows.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In a series of works the so-called *vicinal Cellular Automaton* (vicCA) was proposed and further developed to model the possibly unstable growth and sublimation of vicinal crystal surfaces in 1+1D.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Besides the attachment/detachment events being encoded in the rules of the CA, the adatoms on top of the vicinal form a thin layer, and their thermal motion is modeled by a Monte Carlo module.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] A decisive step further was the transition of the model to 2+1D, where a number of different structures were obtained, referred to by the authors as "vicinal creatures"—step bunches, step meanders, nano-pillars, nanowires, etc.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The vicCA model was extensively used by Alexey Redkov to develop a Machine Learning algorithm on top of it, significantly speeding up calculations by a factor of 105 while enabling systematic classification of the observed phenomena.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automaton processors are physical implementations of CA concepts, which can process information computationally.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Processing elements are arranged in a regular grid of identical cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The grid is usually a square tiling, or tessellation, of two or three dimensions; other tilings are possible, but not yet used.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cell states are determined only by interactions with adjacent neighbor cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] No means exists to communicate directly with cells farther away.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] One such cellular automaton processor array configuration is the systolic array.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cell interaction can be via electric charge, magnetism, vibration (phonons at quantum scales), or any other physically useful means.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This can be done in several ways so that no wires are needed between any elements.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This is very unlike processors used in most computers today (von Neumann designs) which are divided into sections with elements that can communicate with distant elements over wires.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Rule 30 was originally suggested as a possible block cipher for use in cryptography.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Two-dimensional cellular automata can be used for constructing a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have been proposed for public-key cryptography.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] The one-way function is the evolution of a finite CA whose inverse is believed to be hard to find.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Given the rule, anyone can easily calculate future states, but it appears to be very difficult to calculate previous states.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have also been applied to design error correction codes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have been used in generative music and evolutionary music composition and procedural terrain generation in video games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Certain types of cellular automata can be used to generate mazes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Two well-known such cellular automata, Maze and Mazectric, have rulestrings B3/S12345 and B3/S1234.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the former, this means that cells survive from one generation to the next if they have at least one and at most five neighbours.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] In the latter, this means that cells survive if they have one to four neighbours.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] If a cell has exactly three neighbours, it is born.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] It is similar to Conway's Game of Life in that patterns that do not have a living cell adjacent to 1, 4, or 5 other living cells in any generation will behave identically to it.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] However, for large patterns, it behaves very differently from Life.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] For a random starting pattern, these maze-generating cellular automata will evolve into complex mazes with well-defined walls outlining corridors.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Mazectric, which has the rule B3/S1234 has a tendency to generate longer and straighter corridors compared with Maze, with the rule B3/S12345.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Since these cellular automaton rules are deterministic, each maze generated is uniquely determined by its random starting pattern.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] This is a significant drawback since the mazes tend to be relatively predictable.
[src:procedural-generation-games/cellular-automaton] Like some of the graph-theory based methods described above, these cellular automata typically generate mazes from a single starting pattern; hence it will usually be relatively easy to find the way to the starting cell, but harder to find the way anywhere else.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] An **L-system** or **Lindenmayer system** is a parallel rewriting system and a type of formal grammar.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] L-systems were introduced and developed in 1968 by Aristid Lindenmayer, a Hungarian theoretical biologist and botanist at the University of Utrecht.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Lindenmayer used L-systems to describe the behaviour of plant cells and to model the growth processes of plant development.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] L-systems have also been used to model the morphology of a variety of organisms and can be used to generate self-similar fractals.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] As a biologist, Lindenmayer worked with yeast and filamentous fungi and studied the growth patterns of various types of bacteria, such as the cyanobacteria *Anabaena catenula*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Originally, the L-systems were devised to provide a formal description of the development of such simple multicellular organisms, and to illustrate the neighbourhood relationships between plant cells.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Later on, this system was extended to describe higher plants and complex branching structures.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The recursive nature of the L-system rules leads to self-similarity and thereby, fractal-like forms are easy to describe with an L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Plant models and natural-looking organic forms are easy to define, as by increasing the recursion level the form slowly 'grows' and becomes more complex.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Lindenmayer systems are also popular in the generation of artificial life.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] L-system grammars are very similar to the semi-Thue grammar (see Chomsky hierarchy).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The rules of the L-system grammar are applied iteratively starting from the initial state.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] As many rules as possible are applied simultaneously, per iteration.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The fact that each iteration employs as many rules as possible differentiates an L-system from a formal language generated by a formal grammar, which applies only one rule per iteration.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If the production rules were to be applied only one at a time, one would quite simply generate a string in a language, and all such sequences of applications would produce the language specified by the grammar.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] There are some strings in some languages, however, that cannot be generated if the grammar is treated as an L-system rather than a language specification.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For example, suppose there is a rule S→SS in a grammar.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If productions are done one at a time, then starting from S, we can get first SS, and then, applying the rule again, SSS.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] However, if all applicable rules are applied at every step, as in an L-system, then we cannot get this sentential form.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Instead, the first step would give us SS, but the second would apply the rule twice, giving us SSSS.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] An L-system is *context-free* if each production rule refers only to an individual symbol and not to its neighbours.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Context-free L-systems are thus specified by a context-free grammar.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If a rule depends not only on a single symbol but also on its neighbours, it is termed a *context-sensitive* L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If there is exactly one production for each symbol, then the L-system is said to be *deterministic* (a deterministic context-free L-system is popularly called a *D0L system*).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If there are several, and each is chosen with a certain probability during each iteration, then it is a *stochastic* L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Using L-systems for generating graphical images requires that the symbols in the model refer to elements of a drawing on the computer screen.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For example, the program *Fractint* uses turtle graphics (similar to those in the Logo programming language) to produce screen images.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] It interprets each constant in an L-system model as a turtle command.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Lindenmayer's original L-system for modelling the growth of algae.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The result is the sequence of Fibonacci words.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If it is not desired to skip the first 1, axiom *B* can be used.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] That would place a *B* node before the topmost node (*A*) of the graph above.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For each string, if one counts the *k*-th position from the left end of the string, the value is determined by whether a multiple of the golden ratio falls within the interval $(k-1,k)$ .
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The ratio of A to B likewise converges to the golden mean.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This example yields the same result (in terms of the length of each string, not the sequence of *A*s and *B*s) if the rule (*A* → *AB*) is replaced with (*A* → *BA*), except that the strings are mirrored.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This sequence is a locally catenative sequence because $G(n)=G(n-1)G(n-2)$ , where $G(n)$ is the *n*-th generation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The shape is built by recursively feeding the axiom through the production rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Each character of the input string is checked against the rule list to determine which character or string to replace it with in the output string.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In this example, a '1' in the input string becomes '11' in the output string, while '[' remains the same.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] It can be seen that this string quickly grows in size and complexity.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This string can be drawn as an image by using turtle graphics, where each symbol is assigned a graphical operation for the turtle to perform.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The push and pop refer to a LIFO stack (more technical grammar would have separate symbols for "push position" and "turn left").
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] When the turtle interpretation encounters a '[', the current position and angle are saved, and are then restored when the interpretation encounters a ']'.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If multiple values have been "pushed," then a "pop" restores the most recently saved values.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Let *A* mean "draw forward" and *B* mean "move forward".
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This produces the famous Cantor's fractal set on a real straight line **R**.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] A variant of the Koch curve which uses only right angles.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Here, F means "draw forward", + means "turn left 90°", and − means "turn right 90°" (see turtle graphics).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The Sierpinski triangle drawn using an L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Here, F and G both mean "draw forward", + means "turn left by angle", and − means "turn right by angle".
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] It is also possible to approximate the Sierpinski triangle using a Sierpiński arrowhead curve L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Here, A and B both mean "draw forward", + means "turn left by angle", and − means "turn right by angle" (see turtle graphics).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The dragon curve drawn using an L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] First one needs to initialize an empty stack.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This follows the LIFO (Last in, First Out) method to add and remove elements.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Here, F means "draw forward", − means "turn right 25°", and + means "turn left 25°".
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] X does not correspond to any drawing action and is used to control the evolution of the curve.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The square bracket "[" corresponds to saving the current values for position and angle, so the position and angle are pushed to the top of the stack, when the "]" token is encountered, the stack is popped and the position and angle are reset.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] A number of elaborations on this basic L-system technique have been developed which can be used in conjunction with each other.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Among these are stochastic grammars, context sensitive grammars, and parametric grammars.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The grammar model we have discussed thus far has been deterministic—that is, given any symbol in the grammar's alphabet, there has been exactly one production rule, which is always chosen, and always performs the same conversion.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] One alternative is to specify more than one production rule for a symbol, giving each a probability of occurring.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Under this production, whenever a "0" is encountered during string rewriting, there would be a 50% chance it would behave as previously described, and a 50% chance it would not change during production.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] When a stochastic grammar is used in an evolutionary context, it is advisable to incorporate a random seed into the genotype, so that the stochastic properties of the image remain constant between generations.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] A context sensitive production rule looks not only at the symbol it is modifying, but the symbols on the string appearing before and after it.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] As with stochastic productions, there are multiple productions to handle symbols in different contexts.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If no production rule can be found for a given context, the identity production is assumed, and the symbol does not change on transformation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] If context-sensitive and context-free productions both exist within the same grammar, the context-sensitive production is assumed to take precedence when it is applicable.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In a parametric grammar, each symbol in the alphabet has a parameter list associated with it.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] A symbol coupled with its parameter list is called a module, and a string in a parametric grammar is a series of modules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The parameters can be used by the drawing functions, and also by the production rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The production rules can use the parameters in two ways: first, in a conditional statement determining whether the rule will apply, and second, the production rule can modify the actual parameters.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The module a(x,y) undergoes transformation under this production rule if the conditional x=0 is met.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For example, a(0,2) would undergo transformation, and a(1,2) would not.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In the transformation portion of the production rule, the parameters as well as entire modules can be affected.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In the above example, the module b(x,y) is added to the string, with initial parameters (2,3).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Also, the parameters of the already existing module are transformed.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] as the "x" parameter of a(x,y) is explicitly transformed to a "1" and the "y" parameter of a is incremented by one.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Parametric grammars allow line lengths and branching angles to be determined by the grammar, rather than the turtle interpretation methods.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Also, if age is given as a parameter for a module, rules can change depending on the age of a plant segment, allowing animations of the entire life-cycle of the tree to be created.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The bi-directional model explicitly separates the symbolic rewriting system from the shape assignment.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For example, the string rewriting process in the Example 2 (Fractal tree) is independent on how graphical operations are assigned to the symbols.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In other words, an infinite number of draw methods are applicable to a given rewriting system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The bi-directional model consists of 1) a forward process constructs the derivation tree with production rules, and 2) a backward process realizes the tree with shapes in a stepwise manner (from leaves to the root).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Each inverse-derivation step involves essential geometric-topological reasoning.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] With this bi-directional framework, design constraints and objectives are encoded in the grammar-shape translation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In architectural design applications, the bi-directional grammar features consistent interior connectivity and a rich spatial hierarchy.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Historically, the construction of L-systems relied heavily on manual efforts by experts, requiring detailed measurements, domain knowledge, and significant time investment.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The process often involved analyzing biological structures and encoding their developmental rules into L-systems, symbol by symbol.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This labor-intensive method made creating accurate models for complex processes both tedious and error-prone.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] A notable example is Nishida's work on Japanese Cypress trees, where he manually segmented branches from a series of images and identified 42 distinct growth mechanisms to construct a stochastic L-system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Despite the significant effort involved, the resulting system provided only an approximation of the tree's growth, illustrating the challenges of manually encoding such detailed biological processes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This arduous task was described as "tedious and intricate," underscoring the limitations of manual approaches.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The challenges of manual L-system construction are also well-documented in The Algorithmic Beauty of Plants by Przemyslaw Prusinkiewicz and Aristid Lindenmayer.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The book demonstrates how L-systems can elegantly model plant growth and fractal patterns, but the examples often required expert intervention to define the necessary rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Manual construction was further constrained by the need for domain-specific expertise, as seen in other applications of L-systems beyond biology, such as architectural design and urban modeling.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In these fields, creating an accurate L-system required not only an understanding of the L-system formalism but also extensive knowledge of the domain being modeled.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The idea of automating L-system inference emerged to address the inefficiencies of manual methods, which often required extensive expertise, measurements, and trial-and-error processes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This automation aimed to enable the inference of L-systems directly from observational data, eliminating the need for manual encoding of rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Initial algorithms primarily targeted deterministic context-free L-systems (D0L-systems), which are among the simplest types of L-systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] These early efforts demonstrated the feasibility of automatic inference but were severely limited in scope, typically handling only systems with small alphabets and simple rewriting rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For instance, Nakano's work highlighted the challenges of inferring L-systems with larger alphabets and more complex structures, describing the task as "immensely complicated".
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Early tools for L-system inference were often designed to assist experts rather than replace them.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For example, systems that presented a population of potential L-systems to the user, allowing them to select aesthetically pleasing or plausible options, reduced some of the manual burden.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] However, these tools relied heavily on human judgment and did not fully automate the inference process.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Some early algorithms were tightly integrated into specific research domains mainly plant modeling.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] These approaches utilized domain knowledge to constrain the search space and achieve better results.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] However, their reliance on predefined domain-specific rules limited their generalizability and applicability to other areas.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Attempts to create generalized algorithms for L-system inference began with deterministic context-free systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Researchers aimed to infer L-systems from data alone, such as sequences of strings or temporal data from images, without relying on domain-specific knowledge.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Bernard's PhD dissertation, supervised by Dr.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Ian McQuillan at the University of Saskatchewan, represents a significant advancement in L-system inference, introducing the Plant Model Inference Tools (PMIT) suite.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Despite the name, this tool is problem agnostic, and is so-named due to the source of the original funding from the P2IRC project.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The PMIT-D0L tool improved the state-of-the-art by enabling the inference of L-systems with up to 31 symbols, compared to previous algorithms that managed only two.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This was achieved through novel encoding techniques and search-space reduction methods.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The PMIT-DCSL tool further improved the inference of deterministic L-systems by demonstrating that the techniques worked in the context-sensitive case with little modification.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This tool also presented further improvements allowing for the inference of deterministic L-systems with up to hundreds of symbols.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Furthermore, this work and McQuillan's theoretical paper proves the complexity of context-sensitive L-systems inference.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] In an unpublished work, Bernard claims to show that context-sensitivity never changes the fundamental nature of the inference problem regardless of the selection rule.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] That is to say, inferring context-sensitive stochastic L-systems is possible if inferring context-free L-system is possible.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] For stochastic L-systems, PMIT-S0L was developed, which uses a hybrid greedy and genetic algorithm approach to infer systems from multiple string sequences.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] The tool demonstrated the ability to infer rewriting rules and probabilities with high accuracy, a first in the field.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] McQuillan first realized that parametric L-systems could be thought of as stochastic L-systems; however, this did not solve the problem of inferring the parametric selection rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] Using Cartesian Genetic Programming, parametric L-systems could be inferred along with the parametric selection rules so long as the parameter set included time (in order to, provide a sequence to the parameters, but time is a reasonable parameter for any real process).
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] This tool, PMIT-PARAM, successfully inferred complex systems with up to 27 rewriting rules, setting a new benchmark in L-system inference.
[src:procedural-generation-games/l-system] There are many open problems involving studies of L-systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] In computing, **procedural generation** is a method of creating data algorithmically as opposed to manually, typically through a combination of human-generated content and algorithms coupled with computer-generated randomness and processing power.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] In computer graphics, it is commonly used to create textures and 3D models.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] In video games, it is used to automatically create large amounts of content in a game.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Depending on the implementation, advantages of procedural generation can include smaller file sizes, larger amounts of content, and randomness for less predictable gameplay.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] The term *procedural* refers to the process that computes a particular function.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Fractals are geometric patterns which can often be generated procedurally.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Commonplace procedural content includes textures and meshes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Sound is often also procedurally generated, and has applications in both speech synthesis as well as music.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] It has been used to create compositions in various genres of electronic music by artists such as Brian Eno who popularized the term "generative music".
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Procedural generation was originally created as an instrument for video games, aiding in generating levels, textures and complete worlds with little human contribution.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Procedurally generated elements have appeared in video games since the 1990s: *The Elder Scrolls II: Daggerfall* takes place in a mostly procedurally generated world, giving a world roughly two thirds the actual size of the British Isles.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] *Soldier of Fortune* from Raven Software uses simple routines to detail enemy models, while its sequel featured a randomly generated level mode.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Avalanche Studios employed procedural generation to create a large and varied group of detailed tropical islands for *Just Cause*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] *No Man's Sky*, a game developed by games studio Hello Games, is all based upon procedurally generated elements.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] The modern demoscene uses procedural generation to package a great deal of audiovisual content into relatively small programs.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] New methods and applications are presented annually in conferences such as the IEEE Conference on Computational Intelligence and Games and the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Interactive Digital Entertainment.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Particularly in the application of procedural generation with video games, which are intended to be highly replayable, there are concerns that procedural systems can generate infinite numbers of worlds to explore, but without sufficient human guidance and rules to guide these.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Using procedural generation in games had origins in tabletop role playing games (RPG).
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] The leading tabletop system, *Advanced Dungeons & Dragons*, provided ways for the "dungeon master" to generate dungeons and terrain using random die rolls, expanded in later editions with complex branching procedural tables.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Strategic Simulations under license from TSR released the *Dungeon Master's Assistant*, a computer program that generated dungeons based on these published tables.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] *Tunnels & Trolls*, published by Flying Buffalo, was designed primarily around solitary play and used similar procedural generation for its dungeons.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Other tabletop RPGs borrowed similar concepts in procedural generation for various world elements.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Many online tools for Dungeon Masters now use procedural generation to varying degrees.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Prior to graphically oriented video games, roguelike games, a genre directly inspired by *Dungeons & Dragons* adopted for solitary play, heavily utilized procedural generation to randomly produce dungeons, in the same manner that tabletop systems had done.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Such early games include *Beneath Apple Manor* (1978) and the genre's namesake, *Rogue* (1980).
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] The procedural generation system in roguelikes would create dungeons in ASCII- or regular tile-based systems and define rooms, hallways, monsters, and treasure to challenge the player.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Roguelikes, and games based on the roguelike concepts, allow the development of complex gameplay without having to spend excessive time in creating a game's world.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] 1978's *Maze Craze* for the Atari VCS used an algorithm to generate a random, top-down maze for each game.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Some games used pseudorandom number generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] These PRNGs were often used with predefined seed values in order to generate very large game worlds that appeared to be premade.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] *The Sentinel* supposedly had 10,000 different levels stored in only 48 and 64 kilobytes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] An extreme case was *Elite*, which was originally planned to contain a total of 248 (approximately 282 trillion) galaxies with 256 solar systems each.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] However, the publisher was afraid that such a gigantic universe would cause disbelief in players, and eight of these galaxies were chosen for the final version.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Though modern computer games do not have the same memory and hardware restrictions that earlier games had, the use of procedural generation is frequently employed to create randomized games, maps, levels, characters, or other facets that are unique on each playthrough.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] This also extends to power-ups and other items that populate the game's map, selected by the game through procedural generational rules to assure the game feels fair to the player so they feel they have the agency to win the game.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Procedural generation is often used in loot systems of quest-driven games, such as action role-playing games and massive multiplayer online role playing games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Though quests may feature fixed rewards, other loot, such as weapons and armor, may be generated for the player based on the player-character's level, the quest's level, their performance in the quest, and other random factors.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] This often leads to loot having a rarity quality applied to reflect when the procedural generation system has produced an item with better-than-average attributes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] For example, the *Borderlands* series is based on its procedural generation system which can create over a million unique guns and other equipment.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Many open world or survival games procedurally create a game world from a random seed or one provided by the player, so that each playthrough is different.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] These generation systems create numerous pixel- or voxel-based biomes with distribution of resources, objects, and creatures.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] The player frequently has the ability to adjust some of the generation parameters, such as specifying the amount of water coverage in a world.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Procedural generation is also used in space exploration and trading games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] *Elite: Dangerous*, through using the 400 billion known stars of the Milky Way Galaxy as its world basis, uses procedural generation to simulate the planets in these solar systems.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Similarly, *Star Citizen* uses the technology to create seamlessly loaded planets among its hand-crafted universe.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] *Outerra Anteworld* is a video game in development that uses procedural generation and real world data to create a virtual replica of planet Earth in true scale.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] As in video games, procedural generation is often used in film to create visually interesting and accurate spaces rapidly.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] This comes in a wide variety of applications.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] One application is *imperfect factories*, which are used by artists to rapidly generate many similar objects.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] This accounts for the fact that, in real life, no two objects are ever exactly alike.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] For instance, an artist can model a product for a grocery store, and then create an imperfect factory to generate many imperfect copies to populate a whole shelf.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] MASSIVE is a high-end computer animation and artificial intelligence software package used for generating crowd-related visual effects for film and television.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] It was developed to create fighting armies of hundreds of thousands of soldiers for Peter Jackson's *The Lord of the Rings* films automatically.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Coherent noise can be extremely important to procedural workflow in film.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Simplex noise is often faster with fewer artifacts, though an older function called Perlin noise may be used as well.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Coherent noise, in this case, refers to a function that generates smooth pseudo-randomness in *n* dimensions.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Poyck studied how procedurally generated cityscapes can be used to aid social simulations and to train self-driving cars.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Procedural generation plays a pivotal part in the progression of digital twins, which are very detailed virtual replicas of real-world objects used for simulation, analysis, and planning.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Neural networks have recently been employed to refine procedurally generated content.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Combining classic randomization methods with deep learning provides new ways for generating audio, images, 3D objects, and other content types.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] This is especially useful in game level development; reinforcement learning allows the development of agents that play generated levels, serving as automatic content evaluators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Integrating procedural generation with deep learning alters the landscape of digital content creation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Zakaria et al. demonstrated that different deep learning methods for procedurally generating Sokoban levels have different strengths and weaknesses.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Looking ahead, researchers are investigating methods to combine large language models (LLMs) with deep-learning powered procedural generation systems, aiming to enhance their adaptability.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Zakaria suggests that "LLMs combined with reinforcement learning can create procedural assets that evolve dynamically based on real-time feedback".
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] Zakaria investigated the application of advanced deep learning structures such as bootstrapped LSTM (Long short-term memory) generators and GANs (Generative adversarial networks) to upgrade procedural level design.
[src:procedural-generation-games/procedural-generation] They found that "diversity sampling consistently increases the numbers of generated solutions and signatures", showing that hybrid approaches help overcome problems like repetitive patterns or lack of variation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] A **pseudorandom number generator** (**PRNG**), also known as a **deterministic random bit generator** (**DRBG**), is an algorithm for generating a sequence of numbers whose properties approximate the properties of sequences of random numbers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The PRNG-generated sequence is not truly random, because it is completely determined by an initial value, called the PRNG's *seed* (which may include truly random values).
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Although sequences that are closer to truly random can be generated using hardware random number generators, ***pseudorandom number generators*** are important in practice for their speed in number generation and their reproducibility.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] PRNGs are central in applications such as simulations (e.g. for the Monte Carlo method), electronic games (e.g. for procedural generation), and cryptography.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Cryptographic applications require the output not to be predictable from earlier outputs, and more elaborate algorithms, which do not inherit the linearity of simpler PRNGs, are needed.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Good statistical properties are a central requirement for the output of a PRNG.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In general, careful mathematical analysis is required to have any confidence that a PRNG generates numbers that are sufficiently close to random to suit the intended use.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In practice, the output from many common PRNGs exhibit artifacts that cause them to fail statistical pattern-detection tests.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Defects exhibited by flawed PRNGs range from unnoticeable (and unknown) to very obvious.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] An example was the RANDU random number algorithm used for decades on mainframe computers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] It was seriously flawed, but its inadequacy went undetected for a very long time.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In many fields, research work prior to the 21st century that relied on random selection or on Monte Carlo simulations, or in other ways relied on PRNGs, were much less reliable than ideal as a result of using poor-quality PRNGs.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Even today, caution is sometimes required, as illustrated by the following warning in the *International Encyclopedia of Statistical Science* (2010).
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] As an illustration, consider the widely used programming language Java.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Up until 2020, Java still relied on a linear congruential generator (LCG) for its PRNG, which is of low quality (see further below).
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] One well-known PRNG to avoid major problems and still run fairly quickly is the Mersenne Twister (discussed below), which was published in 1998.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Other higher-quality PRNGs, both in terms of computational and statistical performance, were developed before and after this date; these can be identified in the List of pseudorandom number generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In the second half of the 20th century, the standard class of algorithms used for PRNGs comprised linear congruential generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The quality of LCGs was known to be inadequate, but better methods were unavailable.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] A major advance in the construction of pseudorandom generators was the introduction of techniques based on linear recurrences on the two-element field; such generators are related to linear-feedback shift registers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The 1997 invention of the Mersenne Twister, in particular, avoided many of the problems with earlier generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The Mersenne Twister has a period of 219 937 − 1 iterations (≈ 4.3×106001), is proven to be equidistributed in (up to) 623 dimensions (for 32-bit values), and at the time of its introduction was running faster than other statistically reasonable generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In 2003, George Marsaglia introduced the family of xorshift generators, again based on a linear recurrence.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Such generators are extremely fast and, combined with a nonlinear operation, they pass strong statistical tests.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In 2006, the WELL family of generators was developed.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The WELL generators in some ways improves on the quality of the Mersenne Twister, which has a too-large state space and a very slow recovery from state spaces with a large number of zeros.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] They are generally used for generating pseudorandom numbers for large parallel computations, such as over GPU or CPU clusters.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] A PRNG suitable for cryptographic applications is called a *cryptographically-secure PRNG* (CSPRNG).
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] A requirement for a CSPRNG is that an adversary not knowing the seed has only negligible advantage in distinguishing the generator's output sequence from a random sequence.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In other words, while a PRNG is only required to pass certain statistical tests, a CSPRNG must pass all statistical tests that are restricted to polynomial time in the size of the seed.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Though a proof of this property is beyond the current state of the art of computational complexity theory, strong evidence may be provided by reducing to the CSPRNG from a problem that is assumed to be hard, such as integer factorization.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In general, years of review may be required before an algorithm can be certified as a CSPRNG.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] It has been shown to be likely that the NSA has inserted an asymmetric backdoor into the NIST-certified pseudorandom number generator Dual_EC_DRBG.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Most PRNG algorithms produce sequences that are uniformly distributed by any of several tests.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] It is an open question, and one central to the theory and practice of cryptography, whether there is any way to distinguish the output of a high-quality PRNG from a truly random sequence.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] In this setting, the distinguisher knows that either the known PRNG algorithm was used (but not the state with which it was initialized) or a truly random algorithm was used, and has to distinguish between the two.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The security of most cryptographic algorithms and protocols using PRNGs is based on the assumption that it is infeasible to distinguish use of a suitable PRNG from use of a truly random sequence.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The simplest examples of this dependency are stream ciphers, which (most often) work by exclusive or-ing the plaintext of a message with the output of a PRNG, producing ciphertext.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The design of cryptographically adequate PRNGs is extremely difficult because they must meet additional criteria.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The size of its period is an important factor in the cryptographic suitability of a PRNG, but not the only one.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The German Federal Office for Information Security (German: *Bundesamt für Sicherheit in der Informationstechnik*, BSI) has established four criteria for quality of deterministic random number generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] For cryptographic applications, only generators meeting the K3 or K4 standards are acceptable.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Intuitively, an arbitrary distribution can be simulated from a simulation of the standard uniform distribution.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] An early computer-based PRNG, suggested by John von Neumann in 1946, is known as the middle-square method.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The algorithm is as follows: take any number, square it, remove the middle digits of the resulting number as the "random number", then use that number as the seed for the next iteration.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] For example, squaring the number "1111" yields "1234321", which can be written as "01234321", an 8-digit number being the square of a 4-digit number.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] This gives "2343" as the "random" number.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Repeating this procedure gives "4896" as the next result, and so on.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Von Neumann used 10 digit numbers, but the process was the same.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] A problem with the "middle square" method is that all sequences eventually repeat themselves, some very quickly, such as "0000".
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Von Neumann was aware of this, but he found the approach sufficient for his purposes and was worried that mathematical "fixes" would simply hide errors rather than remove them.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Von Neumann judged hardware random number generators unsuitable, for, if they did not record the output generated, they could not later be tested for errors.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] If they did record their output, they would exhaust the limited computer memories then available, and so the computer's ability to read and write numbers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] If the numbers were written to cards, they would take very much longer to write and read.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] On the ENIAC computer he was using, the "middle square" method generated numbers at a rate some hundred times faster than reading numbers in from punched cards.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] The middle-square method has since been supplanted by more elaborate generators.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] A recent innovation is to combine the middle square with a Weyl sequence.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] This method produces high-quality output through a long period (see middle-square method).
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Numbers selected from a non-uniform probability distribution can be generated using a uniform distribution PRNG and a function that relates the two distributions.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] is a number randomly selected from distribution $f(b)$ .
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] This is based on the inverse transform sampling.
[src:procedural-generation-games/pseudorandom-number-generator] Similar considerations apply to generating other non-uniform distributions such as Rayleigh and Poisson.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] A **random seed** (or **seed state**, or just **seed**) is a number (or vector) used to initialize a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] A pseudorandom number generator's number sequence is completely determined by the seed: thus, if a pseudorandom number generator is later reinitialized with the same seed, it will produce the same sequence of numbers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] For a seed to be used in a pseudorandom number generator, it does not need to be random.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] Because of the nature of number generating algorithms, so long as the original seed is ignored, the rest of the values that the algorithm generates will follow probability distribution in a pseudorandom manner.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] However, a non-random seed will be cryptographically insecure, as it can allow an adversary to predict the pseudorandom numbers generated.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] The choice of a good random seed is crucial in the field of computer security.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] When a secret encryption key is pseudorandomly generated, having the seed will allow one to obtain the key.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] High entropy is important for selecting good random seed data.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] Random seeds need to be chosen carefully in order to ensure random number generation.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] If a seed is chosen that doesn't provide actual random results, the numbers given by the PRNG (pseudo random number generator) will not work properly in an application that needs them.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] Charting the output values of a PRNG with a scatter plot is a good way to find out if the seed is working.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] If the graph shows static, then the PRNG is giving random results, but if a pattern appears, the seed needs to be fixed.
[src:procedural-generation-games/random-seed] Random seeds are often generated from the state of the computer system (such as the time), a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator or from a hardware random number generator.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Though *Beneath Apple Manor* predates it, the 1980 game *Rogue*, an ASCII-based game that runs in a terminal or terminal emulator, is considered the forerunner and the namesake of the genre, with derivative games mirroring *Rogue*'s character- or sprite-based graphics.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] These games were popularized among college students and computer programmers of the 1980s and 1990s, leading to hundreds of variants.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Some of the better-known variants include *Hack*, *NetHack*, *Ancient Domains of Mystery*, *Moria*, *Angband*, *Tales of Maj'Eyal*, and *Dungeon Crawl Stone Soup*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The Japanese series of *Mystery Dungeon* games by Chunsoft, inspired by *Rogue*, also fall within the concept of roguelike games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The exact definition of a roguelike game remains a point of debate in the video game community.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] A "Berlin Interpretation" drafted in 2008 defined a number of high- and low-value factors of "canon" roguelike games *Rogue*, *NetHack* and *Angband*, which have since been used to distinguish these roguelike games from edge cases like *Diablo*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] To distinguish these from traditional roguelikes, such games may be referred to as **roguelite** (or rogue-lite) or **roguelike-like**.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Despite this alternative naming suggestion, these games are often referred to as roguelike and use the roguelike tag on various marketplaces such as Steam.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The term "roguelike" came from Usenet newsgroups around 1993, as this was the principal channel the players of roguelike games of that period were using to discuss these games, as well as what the developers used to announce new releases and even distribute the game's source code in some cases.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] With several individual groups for each game, it was suggested that with rising popularity of *Rogue*, *Hack*, *Moria*, and *Angband*, all of which shared common elements, that the groups be consolidated under an umbrella term to facilitate cross-game discussion.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] By the time it was suggested that a group be created to discuss the development of these kind of games in 1998, the "roguelike" term was already established within the community.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] This usage parallels that of "Doom clone", a term used in the 1990s that later evolved into the more generic "first-person shooter".
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Drawing from the concepts of tabletop role-playing games such as *Dungeons & Dragons*, nearly all roguelikes give the player control of a character, which they may customize by selecting a class, or adjusting attributes points and skills.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] In some, further customization through selecting race and gender is possible.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] At the start of the game, the character is placed at the top-most level of a dungeon, with basic equipment such as a simple weapon, armor, torches, and food.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Following along the role-playing concept of a dungeon crawl, the player moves the character through the dungeon, collecting treasure which can include new weapons, armours, magical devices, potions, scrolls, food, and money, while having to fight monsters that roam the dungeon.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Most combat is performed simply by attempting to move the character into the same space as the monster.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The game then calculates the damage that the character and monster deal.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Other types of attacks, such as firing an arrow or performing an offensive magic spell, can often be performed as well.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Defeating monsters earns the character experience points, and after earning enough points, the character will gain an experience level, improving their hit points, magic capability, and other attributes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Monsters may drop treasure to be looted.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The character dies if they lose all their hit points.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] As most roguelikes feature the concept of permadeath, this represents the end of the game, and the player will need to restart the game with a newly made character.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Roguelikes are nearly always turn-based, with the game only reacting when the player makes an action with the character.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] This allows players to evaluate a difficult situation, such as being cornered by several monsters, at their own pace and determine the best strategy.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The player generally has to explore the dungeon to reveal its contents, similar to a fog of war.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Many roguelikes include visibility elements, such as a torch to provide illumination to see monsters in nearby squares, or line of sight to limit which monsters are visible from the player's position.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Dungeons tend to be connected by stairs; lower dungeon levels generally are more difficult than higher ones, so that an underdeveloped character will have difficulty progressing too fast.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Dungeon levels and the population of monsters and treasure within them are generated randomly using procedural generation, so no game is the same on subsequent playthroughs.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Most roguelikes have an ultimate goal of either claiming an item located at the deepest level of the dungeon, or defeating a specific monster that lives on that level.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Typical roguelikes assess the player's performance at the end of the game through a score based on the amount of treasure, money, experience earned, and how fast the player finished the game, if they managed to do so.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The score is displayed in a ranked scoreboard to compare the player's performance on successive runs.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] What gameplay elements explicitly define a "roguelike" game remains a point of debate within the video game community.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Some players and developers sought a more narrow definition for "roguelike" as variations on *Rogue* introduced new concepts or eschewed other principles that they felt moved the games away from the flavor of what *Rogue* was.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] At the International Roguelike Development Conference 2008 held in Berlin, Germany, players and developers established a definition for roguelikes known as the "**Berlin Interpretation**".
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The Berlin Interpretation set out a set of high-value and low-value factors, basing these lists on five canon roguelike games: *ADOM*, *Angband*, *Linley's Dungeon Crawl*, *NetHack*, and *Rogue*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The Interpretation was designed to determine "how roguelike a game is", noting that missing a factor does not eliminate a game from being a roguelike, nor does possessing the features make a game roguelike.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Though this is not addressed by the Berlin Interpretation, roguelikes are generally single-player games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] On multi-user systems, leaderboards are often shared between players.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Some roguelikes allow traces of former player characters to appear in later game sessions in the form of ghosts or grave markings.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Some games such as NetHack even have the player's former characters reappear as enemies within the dungeon.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Multi-player turn-based derivatives such as *TomeNET*, *MAngband*, and *Crossfire* do exist and are playable online.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Early roguelikes were developed to be played on text-based user interfaces, commonly UNIX-based computer mainframes and terminals used at colleges and universities before transitioning to personal computers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Games used a mix of ASCII or ANSI characters to visually represent elements of the dungeon levels, creatures, and items on the level as in ASCII art.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] These games typically included one or two text lines presenting the player's current status at the bottom of the screen, and text-based menu screens to manage inventory, statistics, and other details.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The player's character was nearly always represented by the `@` character across text-based roguelikes, which had been chosen by the developers of *Rogue* to stand for "where you're at".
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Other common examples would include `$` for monetary treasure and `D` for a dragon.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Later games would take advantage of colour-based text graphics to increase the variation of creature types, such as a red `D` for a red dragon that would shoot fire, while a green `D` could indicate a green dragon that would shoot acid.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Players would use the keyboard, using one keypress to enter a command.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Johnson described these commonality of symbols and glyphs as semiotic codes that gave an "aesthetic construction of nostalgia" by "depicting textual symbols as aesthetic forms in their own right" and consistency across multiple roguelikes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] With modern computer systems, users developed alternate means of displaying the game, such as graphical tilesets and Isometric-based graphical front ends, as well as interfaces that took advantage of keyboard and mouse UI controls, but otherwise still kept to the core tile-based gameplay.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] As computers offered more advanced user interfaces, such as windows and point-and-click menus, many traditional roguelikes were modified to include support for having multiple windows.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] This was useful to not only show the character-based dungeon, but details on the character's inventory, the monster they were in battle with, and other status messages, in separate windows.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Having access to multiple windows also allowed having menus to complete more complex commands.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] More recent examples of roguelikes that have stayed with ASCII art-based displays include *Cogmind* (2017) and *Cataclysm: Dark Days Ahead* (2013).
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] With computers and video game consoles capable of more advanced graphics and gameplay, numerous games have emerged that are loosely based on the classic roguelike design but diverge in one or more features.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Many of these games use the concepts of procedurally generated maps and permadeath, while moving away from tile-based movement and turn-based gameplay, often using another gameplay genre such as action games or platformers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Other titles deriving from roguelike games are based on the observation that the traditional roguelikes are difficult with a steep learning curve, and a player may never complete these games over numerous play sessions, making these titles difficult to sell to a broader audience.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] These new games would include elements to reduce the difficulty as to draw in a larger audience.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Many games with some of the Berlin Interpretation elements call themselves "roguelike", but bear little resemblance to the original *Rogue*, causing confusion and dilution of the term.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] As such, the term "**rogue-lite**" or "roguelike-like" has been used by some to distinguish these games that possess some, but not all, of the Berlin Interpretation features from those that exactly meet the Berlin roguelike definition.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The phrase "procedural death labyrinth" has also been applied to such games, as they retain the notion of permadeath and random level generation but lack the other high-value factors normally associated with roguelike games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Rogue-lites favor short gameplay runs with victory conditions, in contrast to some traditional roguelikes that can be played indefinitely.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] The shortness of a single gameplay run in rogue-lites can motivate players to continually replay the game in the hope of reaching completion, making replayability a high-value factor in these types of games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Game journalist Joshua Bycer observed that several games considered as rogue-lites feature fixed events, even if the means to reach that may be through procedural generation, whereas a roguelike game typically lacks this level of predictability.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] For example, several rogue-lites require the player to travel a fixed number of biomes, each which culminates in a boss fight, such as *Rogue Legacy*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Associated with their short length, many rogue-lites feature a metagame, whereby achieving certain goals will unlock persistent features such as the ability to select a new character at the start of the game or the addition of new items and monsters in the procedural generation of the game's levels.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Alternatively, each run through rogue-lite may be to collect resources which one then advances their character within the metagame, and a player may simply forgo a complete run once they have collected sufficient materials for that advancement.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Rogue-lites may also allow the player to enter the random seed directly as to be able to rechallenge the same set of levels or share a difficult set of levels with other players.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] In considering the popularity of roguelikes that deviate from the Berlin Interpretation, the rogue-lites, some subgenres have emerged.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Action roguelikes are typically based on combining gameplay of action games within roguelikes rather than turn-based gameplay.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] *Spelunky* is an example of combining a platform game with the roguelike formula, while *The Binding of Isaac* and *Enter the Gungeon* are roguelike shooter games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] Another type of roguelike subgenre is the roguelike deck-builder, in which combat is resolved by using cards or an equivalent object.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] These games are inspired by physical deck-building games, where the player builds their deck over the course of the game, forcing them to plan strategy on the fly.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p01] While the 2014 game *Dream Quest* is considered the first example of such a video game, the popularity of the genre was cemented with *Slay the Spire* in 2017.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Some elements of the roguelike genre were present in dungeon crawlers written for the PLATO system.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] This includes *pedit5* (1975) believed to be the first dungeon crawl game, and featured random monster encounters, though only used a single fixed dungeon level.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] It is unclear if these PLATO games inspired the roguelike genre as there is no evidence that the early roguelike creators had access to these games.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The core roguelike games were developed independently of each other, many of the developers not learning about their respective projects until several years after the genre took off.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Procedural generation led to high replayability, as no two games were alike.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Though the term "roguelike" derives from the 1980 game *Rogue*, the first known game with the core roguelike gameplay elements was *Beneath Apple Manor* (1978), written by Don Worth for the Apple II; *Beneath Apple Manor* is also recognized as the first commercial roguelike game.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The game, inspired by Worth's enjoyment of *Dungeons & Dragons* roleplaying, included procedural generation using a modification of the random maze generator from the game *Dragon Maze*, role-playing elements for the characters, tile-based movement and turn-based combat.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Another early roguelike whose development pre-dated *Rogue* was *Sword of Fargoal* (1982), developed by Jeff McCord starting in 1979.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The game was based on *GammaQuest*, an earlier title McCord had created on the Commodore PET which he shared locally with friends while a student at Henry Clay High School in Kentucky; the game itself was based on a *Dungeons & Dragons* campaign he had run himself in the prior years.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Before graduating and attending the University of Tennessee in 1981, he had started work on *GammaQuest II*, which required the player to navigate through randomly generated dungeon levels, acquire a sword, and make it back to the surface with that sword through more randomly generated levels.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The more advanced computers available at the school, such as the VIC-20, enabled him to expand out the game further from the highly limited memory on the PET.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The game was considered a success, and when it was ported to the PC in 1983, it out-shone *Rogue*'s PC release the same year due to *Sword of Fargoal*'s superior graphics and sound.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Solid lines represent games developed from the parent's source code, while dotted lines represent games that were inspired by the parent game.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The popularity of *Rogue* led developers to create their own versions of the game, though their efforts were originally limited by the lack of access to *Rogue*'s source, which was not released until BSD v4.3 in 1986.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] These developers resorted to building games from scratch similar to *Rogue* but with features that they wanted to see.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] These versions would be distributed with source code, and along with the original *Rogue* source, other developers were able to create software forks of the games, adding in new monsters, items, and gameplay features, creating several dozen variants.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] This process was aided by switching code to languages with better data typing, including object-oriented and scripting languages, and cleaning up and modularizing the code so that contributors can better follow where changes can be made.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] While there are some direct variants of *Rogue*, such as *Brogue*, most variants of *Rogue* could be classified into two branches based on two key games, *Moria* and *Hack*, that were developed in the spirit of *Rogue*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Once *Angband* was released to the public via USENET, there were efforts to have code maintainers (the "devteam") to fix bugs, clean up the code and implement suggestions into the code.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] One significant fork was *ZAngband* (1994) (short for *Zelazny Angband*), which expanded on *Angband* and altered the theme towards Roger Zelazny's *The Chronicles of Amber*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The *ZAngband* codebase would be used to create *Troubles of Middle Earth* (*ToME*) in 2002, which later swapped out the Tolkien and Zelazny fiction setting for a new original one to become *Tales of Maj'Eyal* (2009).
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The vanilla *Angband* remains in development today by the devteam.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Not all early roguelikes were readily classified as *Hack* or *Moria* descendants.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] *Larn* also uses a fixed-time feature, in that the player had only so many turns to complete a goal, though there were ways to jump back in time as to extend play.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] *Omega*, developed by Laurence Brothers in the late 1980s, is credited with introducing an overworld concept to the roguelike genre, prior to the feature's appearance in *ADOM*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] *Omega* was often remembered for its odd inventory approach in which the player would have to pick up an object, considering it being held, and then moving that object to a bag or an equipment slot.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] *Linley's Dungeon Crawl* (1995) was created by Linley Henzell and featured a skill-based character progression system, in which experience points could be used to improve specific skills, such as weapon proficiency or trap detection.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] One fork of this would form the basis for *Dungeon Crawl Stone Soup* (2006).
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] SSI's *Dungeon Hack* (1993) offered randomized dungeons and permadeath within AD&D 2nd Edition rules.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Through 1993, roguelikes primarily existed in computer space, and no home console variants had yet existed.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Two of the earliest-known attempts were Sega's *Fatal Labyrinth* (1990) and *Dragon Crystal* (1990), but which lacked the depth of a typical computer-based roguelike.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] There was also the 1991 Japanese exclusive Game Boy game *Cave Noire* from Konami, that centred on four distinct roguelike questlines divided into ten difficulty levels.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Chunsoft had gained success by developing the *Dragon Quest* series, a series which established fundamental aspects of the computer role-playing game genre, popular for Western computer audiences, into a more streamlined approach better suited for Japanese players that preferred consoles.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] With roguelikes starting to gain popularity, Chunsoft's developers believed they could do a similar treatment for that genre to make it better suited for Japanese audiences.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Chunsoft's Koichi Nakamura stated their intent was to take *Rogue* and make it "more understandable, more easy-to-play version" of the title that could be played on consoles.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] This led to the creation of the *Mystery Dungeon*, with the first title being *Torneko no Daibōken: Fushigi no Dungeon* (トルネコの大冒険 不思議のダンジョン, *Torneko's Great Adventure: Mystery Dungeon*) (1993) based on the *Dragon Quest* series.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Several changes to the roguelike formula had to be made for this conversion: they had developed ways to reduce the difficulty of the roguelike by using progressively more difficult dungeons that were randomly generated, and made permadeath an option by selection of difficulty level.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] An added benefit for *Torneko no Daibōken* was that it used the established *Dragon Quest 4* setting and the character Torneko, helping to make the game familiar to its planned audience and giving a story for the player to follow.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] While *Torneko no Daibōken* did not sell as well as typical *Dragon Quest* games, it was successful enough for Chunsoft to develop a second title based on a wholly original character and setting, *Mystery Dungeon: Shiren the Wanderer*, released in 1995.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Chunsoft found that they were more creative with how they developed the game without the need to respect an existing property.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Several titles in the *Mystery Dungeon* series were popular, and would become a staple of the Japanese video game market.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The *Mystery Dungeon* games were not as successful in Western markets when published there, as the target players—younger players who likely had not experienced games like *Rogue*—found the lack of a traditional role-playing game save system odd.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Other Japanese role-playing games would incorporate random dungeon generation as part of their design, mimicking part of the nature of roguelikes, and were considered roguelike titles when published in Western markets.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Such titles include *Azure Dreams*, *Dark Cloud*, *Shining Soul*, and *Baroque*.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The massively multiplayer online role-playing game *Final Fantasy XIV* added a randomly generated Deep Dungeon that was inspired by the procedural generation of roguelikes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Though new classical roguelike variants would continue to be developed within the Western market, the genre languished as more advanced personal computers capable of improved graphics capabilities and games that utilized these features became popular.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] However, some of these new graphical games drew influence for roguelike concepts, notably action role-playing games like Blizzard Entertainment's *Diablo* (1996).
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] *Diablo*'s creator, David Brevik, acknowledged that games like *Rogue*, *NetHack*, *Telengard* and other roguelikes influenced the design of *Diablo*, including the nature of randomly generated dungeons and loot.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Existing roguelikes continue to be developed: a sequel to *ADOM* successfully received crowd funding in 2012, while *NetHack*'s first major release in ten years in 2015 is set to help the DevTeam expand the game further.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] New roguelikes that adhere to core Berlin Interpretation rules are still being created, including *Dungeon Crawl Stone Soup* (2006), *Dungeons of Dredmor* (2011), and *Dragon Fin Soup* (2015).
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The roguelike genre saw a resurgence in Western markets after 2000 through independent developers who created a new subgenre designated "rogue-lite", though the games are also sometimes called "roguelike-likes".
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Indie developers began to incorporate roguelike elements into genres not normally associated with roguelikes, creating games that would form the basis of this new subgenre.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Two of the earliest cited examples of rogue-lites are *Strange Adventures in Infinite Space* (2002) and its sequel *Weird Worlds: Return to Infinite Space* (2005) by Digital Eel, both space exploration games that included randomly generated planets and encounters, and permadeath.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The newfound success in rogue-lites is considered part of a larger trend in those that play both board and computer games, looking for "rich play experiences", as described by *100 Rogues* developer Keith Burgun, that more popular titles may not always offer.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Fabien Fischer offers that players have taken to independently developed rogue-lites as they have tired from "superficial gameplay, whitewashing spectacle, the content craze, and Skinner Box design" in titles produced by AAA developers and publishers.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Procedural-generated world lets developers create many hours worth of game content without spending resources on designing detailed worlds.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The roguelike genre has developed with the expansion of both classical roguelikes and rogue-lite titles, a dedicated fan community has come about to not only discuss games within it but to craft their own tales of near-death adventures or amusing stories in roguelikes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] Within this community, there is strong interest in developing roguelikes.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The 7 Day Roguelike challenge (7DRL) was born out of a USENET newsgroup in 2005 for roguelike developers, informally challenging them to create the core of a novel roguelike within 7 days to be submitted for judging and play by the public.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] The competition has continued annually each year, since growing from 5–6 entries in 2005 to over 130 in 2014.
[src:procedural-generation-games/roguelike-p02] In the spirit of the 2008 International Roguelike Conference, the "Roguelike Celebration" was held for the first time in September 2016 in San Francisco where several past and present roguelike developers gathered to discuss the history and future direction of the genre.
